    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "3c1e9f18_1f682fa1",
        "filename": "util/win/exception_handler_server.cc",
        "patchSetId": 24
      },
      "lineNbr": 312,
      "author": {
        "id": 1144260
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-10-21T21:33:25Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Oh, right. We did talk about that in the bug before, I think. That\u0027s part of why the pipe creation happens on the main thread rather than the background thread, so that SendToCrashHandlerServer() won\u0027t fail out immediately with a FILE_NOT_FOUND.\n\nHow about this theory: I\u0027m leaning towards WaitNamedPipe(..., NMPWAIT_WAIT_FOREVER) during connection. The browser creates the handle, inherits it to the handler, and then closes its copy. That means the only system-wide handle remaining is in the handler. So if the handler has failed to start, then there will be nothing for the child to connect to, and it\u0027ll fail out immediately, but without requiring extra data for explicit synchronization.",
      "parentUuid": "fc13270f_9d5ba710",
      "revId": "2d87606bb56bb00ed78ae17f334d7e65af11bcc0",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fc13270f_1d6837a1",
        "filename": "util/win/exception_handler_server.cc",
        "patchSetId": 24
      },
      "lineNbr": 510,
      "author": {
        "id": 1143760
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-10-21T21:01:47Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "…this point\n\nbefore anyone else tries to register.\n\nThis makes the synchronization more important in Chrome. We need to make sure that the handler process has started before starting any other child processes that will try to register with Crashpad. Even better, we’d want to know that the handler has reached this point, not just that its process is alive.\n\nWe left ourselves a nice meaty comment in SendToCrashHandlerServer() (util/win/registration_protocol_win.cc) explaining what’s up. We also left it in a 5-try loop, which affords us some mitigation against child processes being left unregistered with Crashpad, but I’m concerned that if we see lots of child processes trying to spin up at the same time, there’d be a big enough backlog by the time a slow crashpad_handler started dealing with them that we’d lose some.",
      "revId": "2d87606bb56bb00ed78ae17f334d7e65af11bcc0",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    }
